The G-8 Summit took place in Deauville, France, with President Obama and other world leaders attending. They expressed solidarity with Japan after the earthquake and tsunami and pledged continued assistance for recovery efforts. The leaders discussed various global priorities, including supporting democratization in the Middle East and North Africa, promoting economic growth, addressing climate change, ensuring nuclear safety, and addressing security challenges such as terrorism and weapons proliferation. They also renewed the G-8's partnership with Africa and emphasized the importance of human rights, democratic governance, and sustainable development in the continent. The leaders emphasized mutual accountability and aid effectiveness. President Obama announced that the United States would host the G-8 Summit in 2012.